17 neminem causidicum: nemo as an adj. is used only with a personal noun (nemo civis, homo etc.)‚ except in very late Latin, and is generally separated from its substantive (esp. in Cicero) by an intervening word. Cp. Neue, Formenl. 11⁸ p. 522 f. Landgraf, Cic. pro Rosc. Am. p. 374 SchmaIZ, Antib. s. V. It occurs but once in the other writings of Tacitus : Ann. XV 16 neminem Romanum.

The genit. plur. causidicorum of the MSS. absurdly implies the existence of causidici in the golden age which, according to Maternus, was ‘ oratorum ct. criminum inops.’ Baehrens’ defence of Heumann's emendation is the only acceptable item in his long note (Comm. Crit. p. 64), which is prin— cipally devoted to a J'ustification of a most violent transposition in the text. Cp. the excellent discussion of Wiesler Progr. Leoben (1886), pp. 8-10.
